##Children suffering from cancer after the city closure in Wuhan: We should all be well

Micro-signal curekids

Functional Introduction, warm and reliable knowledge of pediatric oncology

INTERVIEW & Editorial | Yan Qing

TYPOGRAPHY | Burson Marsteller

When the city of Wuhan was shut down, a group of children suffering from cancer also stayed in the city. They face not only the epidemic but also the challenges of cancer treatment.

It has been nearly a month since January 23rd. How are the kids that had to stay?

When the city of Wuhan was shut down, a group of children suffering from cancer also stayed in the city. They face not only the epidemic but also the challenges of cancer treatment.

It has been nearly a month since January 23rd. How are the kids that had to stay?

01

A kid with a tumor in his eye

One-year-old 10 months Tong Tong has a pair of big eyes, if ignore the left eye sometimes appear a little white reflection, it is difficult to see that she is a child suffering from cancer.

Tong is suffering from retinoblastoma. It is the most common ocular malignancy in children, affecting about 1,100 children each year across China. The tumor will grow in the eye, the child did not feel at first, but later will slowly blind. If left untreated, the tumor can eventually grow beyond the orbit and spread to other parts of the body.

A child with retinoblastoma looks directly into the camera for a photograph,

There is a white reflection in the pupil (left pupil) .

Image: The web

However, as long as the timely detection and treatment of this tumor, the cure rate is very high. Often, what worries parents is not the cure, but whether the child can keep her eyes -- or, if she misses the chance, remove the eyeball to destroy the tumor and lose the light to save her life.

But neither Tong nor his mother expected that Tong would continue to receive treatment after he returned home to Huangpi District from the hospital on January 14.

Tong Tong was treated in Shanghai before returning to Huangpi District for the New Year. Her tumor wasn't the most advanced stage, which means, with the right treatment, she could keep her big, beautiful eyes, continue to see her mom's smiling face, her favorite amusement parks, her favorite cartoons.

Although Tong Tong's treatment experienced some twists and turns before she came to Shanghai, the good news is that the treatment in Shanghai went smoothly. Tong is not as afraid of hospitals as other children. She likes the nurses and aunts in the hospitals. As soon as she was out of Chemo, she was running around. If she hadn't lost her hair after chemotherapy and shaved it off with her mother, no one would have known she was a child undergoing cancer treatment.

Chemotherapy worked well, and from November to January, Tong's tumor was under control. Mother and the doctor agreed, and so on the end of the year, February 6, will bring Tong to Shanghai, continue treatment. At the time, no one could have predicted that an epidemic was spreading across the country.

On January 23rd, the city of Wuhan was sealed off.

Notice on the official Weibo Account of the city closure in Wuhan.

Image Credit: screenshot via Weibo

January 24th, New Year's Eve. Tong Tong's father back to the local rural home burning incense and ancestor worship, was met in the village Feng village, they were stranded in the village, has not been able to go home.

The news that seals a city as if cast a bomb in the heart of Tong mother, the joy that brings before the treatment is successful is blown to pieces. Thin hope makes her hard to breath: out of the city hopeless, even if can out of the city, Shanghai side, will not necessarily admit children from the infected area. What about Tong Tong's treatment?

02

When a tumor encounters an epidemic,

It often rains in winter in Wuhan. The streets are emptier by the day, and word keeps coming in of the diagnosis of COVID-19 pneumonia. Wet Cold Air into the pants, cold air seems to be about to penetrate into the human bones.

In this weather, Tong Tong's mother went to the local hospital one trip after another. Because Tong's doctor in Shanghai told her that Tong was advised to seek treatment at a local hospital in Huangpi District, he could send Tong's chemotherapy regimen, dosage and list to local doctors, or communicate remotely with local doctors.

With this glimmer of hope, despite knowing the risks of going to the hospital during the outbreak, Tong's mother still ran around the nearby hospital, hoping to find a doctor to treat her daughter.

But it's always a disappointment.

"Your child is too young, " said an oncologist politely. The hospital had three oncology wards, two of which had been requisitioned and turned into COVID-19, "The youngest children we have admitted to the hospital are over 10 years old and have never had a child this young. Not that we don't want to help you, but we don't have any experience with children this young. If something happens, we can't afford it... "

What to do. The anxious moment of taking off cure gnaws the heart of tong mother. She kept scrolling through every piece of media she could see, as if learning more about the news would bring the epidemic to an end and the child back to treatment. But the news of the outbreak is getting more heart-wrenching every day.

Tong Tong Tong is still small, completely do not understand what happened outside, she only know, father has not come home, and mother no longer let her go out to play. Downstairs in the amusement park, her favorite slide is empty, no children to fight with her, but she can not go out.

Photo: UNSPLASH

To add insult to injury, Tong's PICC tube care, also began to become difficult.

The PICC TUBE is a special material catheter that carries medication from the blood vessels of a child's limbs to a large vein in the body's center. With PICC, the children intravenous medication, do not have to put up with to give or have an acupuncture treatment's pain every time, directly through the PICC TUBE can, but also reduce the stimulation of peripheral veins. So, many children with long-term chemotherapy will be fitted with PICC tube.

But the PICC tube also has the inconvenience, one of which must maintain once a week. This maintenance is not something you can do at home, but must be done by a trained nurse. If it's not maintained on time, there's a risk of infection. And for children with already weak immune systems, infection can be life-threatening.

Every Thursday is Tong Tong's routine PICC line maintenance time. Tong Tong Tong mother with Tong Tong came to the local PICC clinic, but saw the door closed, the top affixed to a notice of suspension.

What's going on here? Tong Tong mother doubt his eyes, the last time to do maintenance, clearly said to continue to open diagnosis! She read the notice carefully several times. Yeah, we're closed until further notice.

03

This is a war zone. We're all GONNA be okay

"Please help, my child is in urgent need of hospital treatment! "

Mother Tong Has Lost Count of the number of times she issued such a request for help. All kinds of media, all kinds of charity and public welfare organizations, all kinds of hospitals... she was one after another to make a phone call, a trip to go out again and again, again and again in the online release of information, repeatedly told Tong Tong Tong out of the plight of treatment.

Tong's mother is not the only one who has done so, and many parents of the children in Hubei who have been released from treatment have fallen into the same anxiety. We exchanged information in private: "I heard that this hospital can be treated! " "really? " "I heard that so-and-so hospitals in Hubei will not accept all. " "Some people say that Beijing can be treated, I do not know if it is true or not. " ..

The current outbreak is undoubtedly worrisome, but will the child's tumor wait for the epidemic to end? What if the last thing we need is a diversion or something worse? Parents are afraid to think. Only with an almost instinctive power, ask around, ask for help, greedy for every bit of information that may bring hope.

But for the most part, the information isn't really that useful. Tong Tong from the day of treatment, still in the day-to-day extension.

In addition, Tong's PICC TUBE has not been maintained. It's dangerous, and once the harmful microbes multiply in the PICC Tube, the tube that helps the child fight the tumor, it could become a life-threatening condition.

The procedure of changing dressing of PICC tube.

After consulting Tongtong attending doctor's opinion, Tongtong mother finally decided to take Tongtong to the local hospital in-patient Department, please take out Tongtong body of PICC tube.

Extubation, watching the doctors and nurses skilled operation, red mother heart could not help but lit up a little hope. She could not help saying: "If you can extubate here, can you also help the child hit chemotherapy? We really have no way, the child can not afford to delay. "

"I suggest you bring as few children as possible, " the doctor said quietly.

"Why? "

The doctor's mask covered half of his face, and Tong's mother couldn't see his expression. "We just transferred out of the oncology ward after confirming two cases of COVID-19 infection. During special period, you and your child should be safe... "

This words as if a thunder explosion ring in Tong mother ear. COVID-19! All this time she had been thinking about Tong Tong's tumor, almost forgot that he was in the epidemic area, around the potential risk of infection. No, she did not forget, just never thought that the danger of the epidemic would be so close to her, so close to Tong.

She recalled reading about carriers who were asymptomatic and could infect others, and patients who could get worse without warning. The faces I had seen in the reports had slipped through my eyes: The medical staff who had died of the virus, the police workers who had collapsed from overwork, the patients who had died of their illnesses..

At this moment, Mother Tong finally saw the true face of the epidemic precipitous: This is a war without gunsmoke. It turned out that each of us had already been in the battlefield, and Wuhan, is the front line.

First-line medical staff fighting the epidemic at the Wuhan Shelter Hospital.

Photograph: Chinanews.com

"From that day on, I no longer think about running around, looking for a way to help, looking for a place to receive Tong. " Tong Tong Mother's voice has a kind of experience after the struggle of calm.

She began to pay more attention to the epidemic. She is also affected by children who are infected because their families are sick, and by babies who are born with COVID-19 pneumonia because of mother to child transmission. "It's too bad, " said Mother Tong. "I feel so sad when I think of it. ".

"I've thought about it, and there are a lot of difficulties. But if we don't treat it for now, the worst thing that could happen is that Tong could be transferred or something, but it's all treatable, and as long as the outbreak is under control, treatment is not a problem. But if it gets worse, if we get infected, then there's really no hope."

"Do well what we can, protect ourselves, " Tong's mother said to me earnestly. "The epidemic will surely pass in the end, and we will all be fine. "

Just before the press release, we received the latest news from CCTV news: In order to do a good job in the medical treatment of patients with non-new coronary pneumonia during the epidemic period, especially to meet the medical needs of patients with chronic severe illness, pregnant and lying-in women, children, and hemodialysis patients, some hospitals in Wuhan will accept non-new coronary pneumonia patients. Among them, Wuhan Children's Hospital can receive children patients. This is undoubtedly good news for the children with cancer who remain in Wuhan.

Come on, kids, YOU'RE GONNA BE FINE!
